## Keyboard Navigation JavaScript (Optional Enhancement)

```javascript
// Keyboard navigation support for c-navigation
document.querySelectorAll('.c-navigation').forEach(nav => {
  const links = nav.querySelectorAll('.c-navigation__link');
  let currentIndex = Array.from(links).findIndex(link => 
    link.getAttribute('aria-current') === 'page'
  );
  if (currentIndex === -1) currentIndex = 0;

  nav.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
    switch (e.key) {
      case 'ArrowRight':
      case 'ArrowDown':
        e.preventDefault();
        currentIndex = (currentIndex + 1) % links.length;
        links[currentIndex].focus();
        break;
      case 'ArrowLeft':
      case 'ArrowUp':
        e.preventDefault();
        currentIndex = (currentIndex - 1 + links.length) % links.length;
        links[currentIndex].focus();
        break;
      case 'Home':
        e.preventDefault();
        currentIndex = 0;
        links[currentIndex].focus();
        break;
      case 'End':
        e.preventDefault();
        currentIndex = links.length - 1;
        links[currentIndex].focus();
        break;
    }
  });
});
```

## Design Decisions & Explanation

### 1. ARIA Enhancements
- **`aria-label="Main navigation"`**: Provides a descriptive label for screen readers, distinguishing this nav from other `<nav>` elements on the page.
- **`role="navigation"`**: Explicitly declares the landmark role (redundant for `<nav>`, but ensures compatibility with older assistive tech).
- **`aria-current="page"`**: Applied to the active link, informing screen readers that this link points to the current page. This replaces visual-only active styling.

### 2. Keyboard Navigation
- **`tabindex="0"`** on the active link: Makes it focusable via Tab key.
- **`tabindex="-1"`** on other links: Removes them from the natural tab order, but they remain programmatically focusable via arrow keys.
- **Arrow key support**: Users can navigate between links using Left/Right (or Up/Down) arrows, following the [WAI-ARIA Authoring Practices](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/menubar/) for horizontal navigation.
- **Home/End keys**: Jump to first/last link for efficiency.

### 3. State Management
- **`data-state="active"`** on the current page link, alongside `aria-current="page"`. This dual approach ensures both visual styling (via CSS) and semantic meaning (via ARIA) are maintained.
- **`data-state="disabled"`** available for future use (e.g., a link to a page the user doesn't have access to).

### 4. Golden Rule Compliance
- The `.c-navigation` root has **no margin**. External spacing is handled by the `.l-navigation-wrapper` layout class.

### 5. Token Usage
- All values use `var(--token)` — no magic numbers.
- Colors, spacing, typography, and borders are all token-driven for consistency.

### 6. RDFa Annotations
- `typeof="mcs:Component"` — identifies this as an MCSS component.
- `property="mcs:taxonomyLevel" content="mcs:Molecule"` — navigation is a molecule composed of atoms (links).
- `property="mcs:purpose" content="Primary site navigation with keyboard accessibility"` — describes the component's role.
- `data-mcs-interaction-type="click, keyboard"` — documents supported interaction methods.
- `data-mcs-consequence="Navigates to selected page section"` — describes the outcome.
- `data-mcs-triggers-event="navigation:change"` — custom event emitted on navigation.

### 7. Accessibility Testing Checklist
- [ ] Screen reader announces "Main navigation landmark" when entering the nav.
- [ ] Screen reader announces "Home, link, current page" for the active link.
- [ ] Tab key focuses the active link first.
- [ ] Arrow keys move focus between links.
- [ ] Home/End keys jump to first/last link.
- [ ] Focus-visible ring appears on keyboard focus.
- [ ] All interactive elements have visible focus indicators.

This enhanced component provides a robust, accessible navigation experience that works for keyboard users, screen reader users, and mouse users alike.
